Before Russia=E2=80=99s full-scale invasion three years ago, Zelensky drove
Democrats crazy. He publicly criticized ( https://nypost.com/2022/01/20/vol=
odymyr-zelensky-blasts-joe-biden-over-minor-incursion-comment/?utm_campaign=
=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F3%2F25%29&utm_content=3D=
The+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F3%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demai=
l_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) Biden. He=
 publicly disputed American intelligence that Russia was about to invade hi=
s country and chided the Biden administration for issuing such warnings and=
 spooking investors. He showed up in Washington with a long and loud list o=
f demands=E2=80=94and then met with and publicly praised
Ted Cruz while the senator was holding up all of Biden=E2=80=99s State Depa=
rtment nominees over the president=E2=80=99s refusal to sanction the Nord S=
tream 2 pipeline from Russia to Germany. As I reported ( https://puck.news/=
inside-the-biden-putin-chess-match/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brighte=
st+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F3%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+=
-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F3%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcusto=
mer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) a month before Russian tanks poured =
over Ukraine=E2=80=99s border, Biden and D.C. Dems had just about had it wi=
th Zelensky=E2=80=99s antics, which they saw as entitled and tone
deaf.

But then the war began, and everyone closed ranks around a Ukrainian presid=
ent who more than rose to the occasion, and a country that was being savage=
d by Russia in ways too horrifying to bear. In the first months after the i=
nvasion on February 24, 2022, administration officials wouldn=E2=80=99t eve=
n admit off the record that there were any frustrations with Zelensky.

Now, after Friday=E2=80=99s meltdown, the disappointment is palpable once a=
gain among Democrats. They are, of course, furious
and disgusted by Trump and Vance=E2=80=99s treatment of Zelensky and Ukrain=
e, but they also feel that Friday=E2=80=99s meeting was too important to fu=
ck up=E2=80=94and that, given the stakes, Zelensky should have played it sm=
arter. =E2=80=9CHe can be difficult, we know this,=E2=80=9D said the former=
 senior Biden administration official. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s stubborn and h=
e doesn=E2=80=99t take advice, and it=E2=80=99s really, really hard for him=
 to think creatively. Everyone has these problems; he just seems to have a =
harder time hiding it than others.=E2=80=9D Others see
what happened as part of a far more fundamental problem. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=
=99s too arrogant,=E2=80=9D one Democratic foreign policy insider told me. =
=E2=80=9CThinks that if he can only get face to face with Trump, he can cha=
rm him. It never works. Not for Zelensky, not for Macron.=E2=80=9D

One Democratic Senate source pinned the blame not so much on Zelensky as on=
 his advisor, Andriy Yermak. It is Yermak, this extremely pro-Ukraine sourc=
e contended, who has gotten Zelensky in trouble in Washington by
overestimating his own abilities as a D.C. fixer. =E2=80=9CYermak has alway=
s been a bit too big for his britches,=E2=80=9D the source said. Following =
Yermak=E2=80=99s lead, the Ukrainians =E2=80=9Cthink they understand Americ=
an politics better than they do. They think they can play both sides, go di=
rectly to the people, but they=E2=80=99re just not as good as they think th=
ey are.=E2=80=9D

As evidence, both the Democratic Senate source and the Democratic foreign p=
olicy insider brought up the same unforced error that Vance highlighted
in the Oval: Zelensky=E2=80=99s September visit to a Pennsylvania munitions=
 factory alongside Democratic Governor Josh Shapiro. Going to a battlegroun=
d state in the final stretch of the race alongside a major Harris campaign =
surrogate (and erstwhile running mate contender) made Zelensky look like he=
 was picking a side. Harris lost, and now the MAGA side=E2=80=94which has b=
een anti-Zelensky since Trump=E2=80=99s first 2019 impeachment, for which t=
hey hold the Ukrainian president
responsible=E2=80=94hates him even more.

=E2=80=9CThey were playing around in shit they shouldn=E2=80=99t have,=E2=
=80=9D the Democratic Senate source fumed. =E2=80=9CIt showed a real dumbne=
ss about American electoral politics. Do you really think anyone in Pennsyl=
vania is going to vote for the Democrats because the president of Ukraine g=
ot up on a stage? Even the idea that that would help us is based on a misun=
derstanding of how our politics work. The whole thing was pointless, and no=
w has given everyone a talking point that
Zelensky was campaigning for Trump=E2=80=99s opponent.=E2=80=9D

After the Pennsylvania event resulted in a G.O.P. uproar ( https://www.poli=
tico.com/live-updates/2024/09/24/congress/probing-zelenskyys-pa-visit-00180=
794?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F3%2F25%2=
